Curator's comments: The portrait probably dates from the later 30s or early 20s BC, by which time Octavian had abandoned the beard worn as a sign of mourning or vengeance for Caesar's murder, and adopted a style  reminiscent of Hellenistic Greek monarchs.
Description: Seal of glass paste imitating sard: with a bust of Octavian in intaglio: the head, in profile to the left, shows abundant hair falling on the brow in the style of Hellenistic royal portraits. Behind the fringe is a fillet tied at the nape of the neck. The bust is cropped just below the neck, in the fashion of contemporary portraits in stone. Immediately below the bust is a Capricorn; balanced on its back is a theatrical mask and above that a cornucopia.
Marble portrait head of youthful Augustus(?).

Curator's comments: The altar depicted is that set up as the central point of the "Concilium Galliarum" and is likely to have been dedicated by Augustus on 1 August 10 BC, (the same day of the birth in that city of the future emperor Claudius).

Curator's comments: This coin was produced at the town of Colonia Nemausus, ancient Nîmes in the south of France, in about AD 10-14. The designs show Augustus, the first Roman emperor (reigned 31 BC - AD 14) on the right, with his general, Agrippa (died 12 BC). They are shown as victors of the great Roman civil war against Augustus' rival, Mark Antony and his lover, Cleopatra VII, queen of Egypt. The war was portrayed by the victors very much as a battle against 'foreign' domination, despite the involvement of the distinguished Roman, Mark Antony. To emphasize this, the crocodile is used to symbolize Egypt - chained to a palm tree to indicate its defeat and occupation by Rome.
Description: Copper alloy coin; with apendage shaped like a pig's trotter (possibly a votive offering).(obverse) Heads of Augustus, laureate (on right) and Agrippa, laureate and wearing rostral crown (on left), back to back.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Script': u'Latin', u'Inscription Content': u'IMP DIVI F', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: The reverse type probably refers to the triumph early in AD 9, which Tiberius had not been able to celebrate until AD 12 due to the defeat of Varus against the Teutons in AD 9.

Curator's comments: These medallions or phalerae are seen as an attempt to promote members of the imperial family after the death of Augustus. They were probably issued as sets of nice as parade decorations, and were worn on the breast plate.

Curator's comments:
He originally wore a laurel wreath; this was replaced, probably in the medieval period, with the current setting of jewels.
Provenance is unknown; the first recorded mention appears to be  A.F. Gori, Gemmae antiquae ex thesauro Mediceo et privatorum Dactyliothecis Florentiae, I (Florence, 1731), 47-48, who describes it as being in the Strozzi cabinet in Florence.
Cf. unpublished thesis by Lara Schwarz, Van de rug af gezien. De Duc de Blacas camee in het British Museum (Amsterdam 1993)

Curator's comments: In 20 BC, Augustus scored a diplomatic coup by recovering the legionary eagles and standards (SIGNIS) which had been lost to the Parthians by Crassus in 53 BC, thereby erasing the stain of that earlier military disaster. The treaty also provided for the return of surviving Roman captives, who had been in Parthian hands for 33 years.

Curator's comments: In 20 BC, Augustus scored a diplomatic coup by recovering the legionary eagles and standards (SIGNIS) which had been lost to the Parthians by Crassus in 53 BC, thereby erasing the stain of that earlier military disaster. The treaty also provided for the return of surviving Roman captives, who had been in Parthian hands for 33 years. Augustus refused the Senate's offer of a full Triumph, but allowed his triumphal insignia (an eagle-tipped sceptre, a laurel crown, and his purple cloak) to be displayed in the temple of Mars Ultor. Augustus later ranked this among his proudest achievements, because it was attained without the bloodshed or expense of war.
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, bare, right.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'CL.V', u'Inscription Position': u'reverse', u'Inscription Comment': u'on shield', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}, {u'Inscription Content': u'CAESAR AVGVSTVS', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'anti-clockwise', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: In the Res Gestae, Augustus records that the Senate, in giving him the title Augustus, also decreed that the doorposts of his house be officially decorated with laurel, that the corona civica be placed over the door and that a shield be displayed in the Curia Iulia. This shield, or clipeus, had been dedicated to him by the Senate and the Roman People on account of his virtues of bravery, clemency, justice, and piety; virtues which were inscribed on the shield itself. The return in 19 BC of the Roman standards captured by the Parthians in earlier conflicts offered an excellent opportunity to once again recall Augustus' pietas, one of the virtues recorded on the clipeus.
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, bare, right.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'S.P.Q.R. CL.[V]', u'Inscription Position': u'reverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'on shield', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: In the Res Gestae, Augustus records that the Senate, in giving him the title Augustus, also decreed that the doorposts of his house be officially decorated with laurel, that the corona civica be placed over the door and that a shield be displayed in the Curia Iulia. This shield, or clipeus, had been dedicated to him by the Senate and the Roman People on account of his virtues of bravery, clemency, justice, and piety; virtues which were inscribed on the shield itself. The return in 19 BC of the Roman standards captured by the Parthians in earlier conflicts offered an excellent opportunity to once again recall Augustus' pietas, one of the virtues recorded on the clipeus.
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, bare, right.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'S.P.Q.R.CL.V', u'Inscription Position': u'reverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'below', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: This coin was struck in the period when Augustus and his lieutenants carried out the military pacification of areas in Gaul and lower Germany. The type was issued for use by soldiers, hence the militaristic imagery of the legionary eagle on the reverse.

Curator's comments: The colony of Emerita Augusta (modern Mérida) was founded in 25 BC by Publius Carisius, governor of Lusitania, for veterans of legions V Alauda and X Gemina who had recently participated in Augustus' campaigns in north western Spain. The emperor received his initial grant of tribunician power in 1 July 23 BC.
Description: Copper alloy coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, bare, right.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'CAESAR.AVG. TRIB.POTEST.', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'clockwise', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: The colony of Emerita Augusta (modern Mérida) was founded in 25 BC by Publius Carisius, governor of Lusitania, for veterans of legions V Alauda and X Gemina who had recently participated in Augustus' campaigns in north western Spain. The emperor received his initial grant of tribunician power in 1 July 23 BC.
Description: Copper alloy coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, bare, right.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'CAESAR.AVGVS. [TRIBVN POTEST]', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'clockwise', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: Augustus reopened the mint of Rome in 18 BC and reconstituted the board of three moneyers (as opposed to the earlier four). This is signified by the reverse legend, where the generic part after the moneyer's name stands for the Latin tres viri "auro argento aere flando feriundo" (AAAFF).

Curator's comments: The cippus, set up in Rome's Regio VII, records Augustus' generosity in making special contributions to the public treasury in order to help finance the restoration of the public roads. Work on the Via Flaminia was undertaken entirely at his expense, as it was necessary to make the route suitable for the frequent passage of armies
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, bare, right.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'AVGVSTVS TR.POT VIII', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'anti-clockwise', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}, {u'Inscription Content': u'S.P.Q.R IMP.CAE QVOD.V M.S.EX EA.P.QIS AD.A.DE', u'Inscription Position': u'reverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'on cippus', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: This is quite a rare coin minted in 16 BC, the 7th & 8th years of Augustus's tribunician power by L. Vinicius. It is believed that the arch pictured is one built on the Milvian bridge to fortify the Tiber crossing of the Via Flaminia.

Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'S.P.Q.R IMP CAE', u'Inscription Position': u'reverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'on arch', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Description: Alloy coin.

Curator's comments: This CA in wreath type is thought to be attributable to the mint at Pergamum. The exact meaning of CA on this coinage is not known. RPC suggests that C(aesar) A(ugustus) is perhaps the best explanation, although some believe that CA is a representation of honorific wreaths to Augustus by the C(ommune) A(siae).
Description: Copper alloy coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, bare, right.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'AVGVSTV[S]', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'upwards', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: Augustus reopened the mint of Rome in 18 BC and reconstituted the board of three moneyers (as opposed to the earlier four). This is signified by the reverse legend, where the generic part after the moneyer's name stands for the Latin tres viri "auro argento aere flando feriundo" (AAAFF).
Description: Copper alloy coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, bare, right.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'[CAESAR AVG]VST PONT M[AX TRIBVNIC POT]', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'clockwise', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}, {u'Inscription Content': u'AV[...]', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Type': u'countermark'}, {u'Inscription Content': u'[P.LVRIVS.]AGRIPPA.IIIVIR[.A.A.A.F.F.]', u'Inscription Position': u'reverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'clockwise', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: Augustus reopened the mint of Rome in 18 BC and reconstituted the board of three moneyers (as opposed to the earlier four). This is signified by the reverse legend, where the generic part after the moneyer's name stands for the Latin tres viri "auro argento aere flando feriundo" (AAAFF).

Curator's comments: The Roman city of Nemausus (modern Nîmes) in southern Gaul issued a large coinage throughout Augustus' reign with the standard reverse design of a crocodile chained to a palm branch and the ties of a laurel wreath flying above. The crocodile clearly stands for Egypt or more specifically Cleopatra, tied like a dog to the two classic symbols of Roman victory. It may also refer to the presence of veterans of the Actium campaign settled in Nîmes by Octavian. These coins circulated widely in Gaul and on the northern frontier of the empire. The obverse shows the busts of Augustus (right) and his great friend and chief lieutenant, Marcus Vipsanius Agrippa (left).
Description: Copper alloy coin.(obverse) Heads of Augustus, laureate (on right) and Agrippa, laureate and wearing rostral crown (on left), back to back.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Script': u'Latin', u'Inscription Content': u'COL NEM', u'Inscription Position': u'reverse field', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: Struck to commemorate Augustus' and Agrippa's victory at the naval battle of Actium over the forces of Marcus Antonius and Cleopatra, the battle which saw Augustus (then known as Octavian) become undisputed master of the Roman world.
Description: Silver coin; ancient forgery.(obverse) Head of Augustus, laureate, left.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'AVGVSTVS DIVI.F', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'anti-clockwise', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}, {u'Inscription Content': u'IMP XII', u'Inscription Position': u'reverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: This refers to the extensive measures taken by Augustus to improve the road system in Italy. The depiction on reverse may be that of the Milvian Bridge which carried the Via Flaminia, Italy's great nothern highway, across the Tiber just north of Rome. The historian Dio Cassius records the erection of "statues on arches on the bridge over the Tiber" in commemoration of the emperor's munificence in personally financing the work carried out on the Via Flaminia.
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, bare, left.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'QVOD VIAE.MVN.SVNT', u'Inscription Position': u'reverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'anti-clockwise', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: The Roman city of Nemausus (modern Nîmes) in southern Gaul issued a large coinage throughout Augustus' reign with the standard reverse design of a crocodile chained to a palm branch and the ties of a laurel wreath flying above. The crocodile clearly stands for Egypt or more specifically Cleopatra, tied like a dog to the two classic symbols of Roman victory. It may also refer to the presence of veterans of the Actium campaign settled in Nîmes by Octavian. These coins circulated widely in Gaul and on the northern frontier of the empire. The obverse shows the busts of Augustus (right) and his great friend and chief lieutenant, Marcus Vipsanius Agrippa (left).
Description: Copper alloy coin.(obverse) Heads of Augustus, bare-headed (on right) and Agrippa, laureate and wearing rostral crown (on left), back to back.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Script': u'Latin', u'Inscription Content': u'IMP DIVI F', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Description: Pottery: coarse ware unguentarium; mid-brown clay with frequent fine lime; mid-red slip on exterior of neck; thickened flaring rim, flattened on upper surface; tall cylindrical neck tapering to elongated ovoid body with flat base; rim missing.

Curator's comments: Agrippa, Augustus’ lifelong friend and colleague, died the year following this issue, which probably commemorates the renewal of Agrippa’s tribunician power.

Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'CAESAR  AVGVSTVS', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'anti-clockwise', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: Augustus reopened the mint of Rome in 18 BC and reconstituted the board of three moneyers (as opposed to the earlier four). This is signified by the reverse legend, where the generic part after the moneyer's name stands for the Latin tres viri "auro argento aere flando feriundo" (AAAFF).
Description: Copper alloy coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, laureate, left; crowned by Victory, behind, holding cornucopia in left hand and with right touching fillet of laurel-wreath. Neck of Augustus terminates in globe.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'CAESAR.AVGVST.PONT.MAX.TRIBVN  IC.POT', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'clockwise', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}, {u'Inscription Content': u'M.MAECILIVS.TVLLVS.III.VIR.A.A.A.F.F.', u'Inscription Position': u'reverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'clockwise', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Oval fragment of polychrome glass inlay: blue, red and white flowers on gold ground; from a total of twenty-two glass fragments registered under this number.
Gold finger-ring with relief decoration depicting busts of Isis and Serapis, and the head of their son Harpocrates.

Gold ear-ring, in the form of Eros holding a cord in both hands across his middle. His wings are covered with dots. The figure is attached by a loop to a gold hook; soldered to the hook is a disc bordered by plain and beaded wires, and decorated in the centre with a rosette of six wire circles.

Gold ear-ring, in the form of Eros holding a cord in both hands across his middle. His wings are covered with dots. The figure is attached by a loop to a gold hook; soldered to the hook is a disc bordered by plain and beaded wires, and decorated in the centre with a rosette of seven wire circles.

Gold ear-ring pendant in the form of a nude Eros bent back in a bow, his hands on his hips, his feet attached to a small platform from which the ring sprang. Behind his head is soldered a small tube for the insertion of the open end of the ring.

Glass finger-ring; yellow translucent glass with an opaque yellow band twisted spirally around the hoop; in the oval bezel, within an opaque white border, is inserted a convex oval of opaque blue glass.
Bronze plate inscribed in dotted letters, retrograde: Q CARMINIVS OPTATVS LARIBVS.

Gold finger-ring; two hollow hoops soldered side by side; between them are two twisted wires imitating a plaited wire; on either side is a beaded wire; underneath is a 'nodus Herculeus' with three pointed leaves on either side; pointed oval settings, in one of which remains a garnet.
Oval gold plate from the bezel of a finger-ring; inserted in the plate is a burnt sard(?) intaglio, representing a female portrait head to left; the stone is cut into the exact shape of the head.

Glass finger-ring; deep claret-coloured glass hoop; in the flattened bezel is inserted a hollow disc of opaque white glass; a series of irregular circles is scratched on the bezel and shoulders of the ring.
Glass finger-ring; hoop of transparent glass with yellow band twisted spirally round it; flattened oval bezel, with a circular piece of blue glass with yellow border attached to it.
Glass finger-ring; thin round hoop of yellow translucent glass, with small flattened oval bezel.
Bone finger-ring; bezel hollowed out into an oblong form; within this are a sun's disc and two uraei(?) carved in relief.
Chalcedony finger-ring; flattened oval bezel with engraved design: two torches turned obliquely towards each other, with blazing ends touching; inscribed (in reverse direction) S E A.
Chalcedony finger-ring with plain hoop; flattened oval bezel.
Dark blue glass finger-ring; outside decorated with a series of cross-hatched lines; a line of raised ovals runs vertically along the middle of the hoop.
Dark blue glass finger-ring; outside decorated with a series of cross-hatched lines; a line of raised ovals runs vertically along the middle of the hoop.
Iron finger-ring; circular bezel with engraved design: female(?) figure standing and holding an object in her uplifted hand.
Iron finger-ring; oval bezel with inset silver plate; engraved design: head of Athene, wearing helmet.
Iron finger-ring; oval bezel with engraved design: winged female figure (Fortuna-Isis?) wearing horns and disk; she is draped and carries a sistrum and rudder.
Bronze finger-ring; oval bezel with nicolo intaglio: bird to left, about to pick up some object from the ground.
Bronze finger-ring; oval bezel with dark blue paste intaglio: Venus, with drapery over her right arm, stands with her left arm resting upon an altar, over which a cupid flies.

Bronze finger-ring with remains of gilding; oval sard intaglio in the form of a truncated cone: Helios, wearing radiated crown and holding whip, stands opposite a draped male figure who holds a staff; in the field, near the Helios, are a crescent and two stars.
Bronze finger-ring; hoop gold-plated; oval bezel with nicolo intaglio: satyr with goat beneath tree, satyr on rock playing lyre, and a third satyr standing and playing the double flutes.
Bronze finger-ring; oval bezel with burnt sard(?) intaglio: Hekate in triple form, holding up torches; inscribed (in reverse direction): M A P.
Bronze finger-ring; small oval gold plate, separately inserted, with engraved design: bird to left, with two cherries(?) hanging from his beak.
Bronze finger-ring; oval paste intaglio (imitating nicolo): Cupid on dolphin; lower part of hoop broken away.
Bronze finger-ring; in the bezel is set an oval dark blue paste intaglio: Cupid seated on a rock to right; traces of engraved decoration on the shoulders.
Bronze finger-ring; oval nicolo intaglio: beardless portrait head to left; traces of gilding.
Bronze finger-ring; oval sard intaglio: rude figure of Fortuna wearing wreath and holding cornucopia and libation bowl.
Bronze finger-ring; oval bezel with sard intaglio: Cupid holding butterfly.
Bronze finger-ring; bezel formed by two masks side by side; one is bearded and has a fillet over the forehead (Dionysos), the other is beardless with squat features and wide open mouth (satyr).
Bronze finger-ring; large flattened oval bezel with engraved design: two draped Egyptian deities stretching out each an arm towards an upright rod surmounted by a disc(?).

Bezel and shoulders of a bronze finger-ring; large oval bezel with engraved design: festooned altar from which rises an object inlaid with silver, surmounted by a crescent inlaid with gold; the altar has been inlaid with silver and the festoon with gold.
Bronze finger-ring; large oval bezel with engraved design: Victory standing to left, holding out a palm-branch.

Bronze key-ring; flattened oval bezel with an engraved design of the hawk of Horus; in the field are the letters 'Cn. Piso'(?); the key projects from the back of the ring, and is in the form of the 'ankh'.
Bronze finger-ring; oval bezel with convex garnet intaglio: bunch of grapes; the back of the hoop is in the form of a flat projection, with inscription; gilt.
Bronze finger-ring; flattened oval bezel with engraved design: grotesque figure wearing uraeus crown(?), and holding one stick with his raised left and another with his lowered right hand.
Bronze finger-ring; circular bezel with engraved design: Isis walking to left, holding out uraeus.
Silver finger-ring; oval bezel containing a convex sard intaglio: butterfly.
Silver finger-ring; oval sard intaglio (partly broken away): lower part of draped female figure holding staff.
Silver finger-ring; oval bezel; yellow jasper intaglio: Fortuna standing, with cornucopia and steering oar.

Silver finger-ring; large flattened oval bezel into which is inserted a heliotrope with engraved design: Abraxas, with cock's head, human body and serpent legs, holding whip and shield; inscription within the shield.
Bronze finger-ring; oval sard intaglio: Poseidon-Serapis, wearing animal's skin and modius(?), and holding trident; underneath the hoop is an irregular projection.
Silver finger-ring; broad bezel; oval sardonyx intaglio in the form of a truncated cone: Cupid leaning on a pick-axe; only a portion of the hoop remains.
Silver finger-ring; hoop ends in serpents' heads; between the mouths of the serpents is a silver plate (partly broken away), with bust of Sol in relief.
Silver finger-ring; flattened oval bezel with engraved design: palm-branch, the letter 'Z' and an uncertain sign; below the branch is the letter 'A'.
Silver finger-ring; raised oval setting with sard intaglio: Fortuna holding cornucopia and steering oar.
Silver finger-ring; oval bezel with raised sard intaglio: hound catching hare; on one shoulder is engraved TOT.
Gold finger-ring; composed of four flat hoops with narrow oval bezels.
Gold finger-ring; hoop of wire twisted spirally; bezel in the form of a 'nodus Herculeus'.
Gold finger-ring; bezel formed of three wires; the central is beaded, the two outer plain wires are in the form of a 'nodus Herculeus'; bezel is hollow and in the form of a sandal.
Gold finger-ring; small white oval stone streaked with green.

Gold finger-ring; flat hoop, branching into three at the shoulders; at the head are three circular settings: the central contains a paste imitating sapphire, the outer contain pastes imitating an amethyst and a jacinth respectively.
Gold finger-ring; hoop of thick wire twisted spirally; bezel in the form of a 'nodus Herculeus'.
Gold finger-ring; broad hoop; convex oval garnet in high gold setting; on either shoulder are two ivy leaves in filigree with a small rosette between them.

Gold finger-ring; hoop in the form of a ribbon, angular on the outside and tapering towards the ends, one of which is in the shape of a swan's head; oval box-setting containing a convex oval green paste.
Gold finger-ring; narrow hollow hoop rising into very long and narrow pointed oval bezel; bezel contains a raised sardonyx cut to a sharp edge at either extremity.
Gold finger-ring; thin hoop; round bezel set with convex garnet.
Gold finger-ring; thin hoop, convex without, concave within; raised oval setting surrounded by a ring of globules; it contains an amethystine garnet in form of a truncated cone.
Gold finger-ring; bezel contains a round convex garnet; the hoop is hollow and considerably crushed. The stone does not appear to fit the bezel.

Gold finger-ring; narrow hoop, angular without; pointed oval garnet in gold setting; the stone is held in position by four claws in the form of ivy leaves, and the setting is bordered by a beaded wire which terminates at either end in pairs of spirals.
Gold finger-ring; flat hoop, expanding at the head into an oval bezel, in which is set an oval convex garnet.
Gold finger-ring; thin rounded hoop, expanding into an oval bezel with convex oval garnet in raised setting.
Gold finger-ring; thin flat hoop, slightly broadening upwards; on the head is engraved a palm branch, with the letter 'A' on the left and the letter 'E' on the right.
Gold finger-ring; thin gold, with convex bezel; inscribed 'ZOH'; on either side of the 'H' is a palm branch, below are three dots.
Gold finger-ring; thin gold, with convex bezel, much crushed; inscribed in dotted letters.
Gold finger-ring; flat polygonal hoop of thin gold, broadening upwards; convex bezel; inscribed above and below in two lines, with a palm branch between the lines.
Gold finger-ring; plain hoop broadening out towards the almost circular bezel; the hoop is concave within; inscribed.
Gold finger-ring; plain hoop broadening out towards the oval bezel; the hoop is concave within; inscribed.
Pale gold finger-ring; plain hoop broadening out towards the oval bezel; the hoop is concave within; inscription made with dotted letters.
Gold finger-ring; plain hoop broadening out towards the oval bezel; the hoop is concave within; inscription made with letters composed of dots and lines.
Gold finger-ring; plain hoop broadening out towards the oval bezel; the hoop is concave within; inscription made with dotted letters.
Gold finger-ring; flat polygonal hoop of thick gold, broadening upwards; rectangular bezel inscribed above and below in two lines.
Gold finger-ring; plain hoop broadening out towards the oval bezel; the hoop is concave within; inscribed with letters made up of dots and lines.
Gold finger-ring; plain hoop broadening out towards the oval bezel; the hoop is concave within; inscribed in dotted letters.
Gold finger-ring; thin flat hoop broadening upwards; flattened oval bezel with inscription in dotted letters.
Gold double finger-ring; two thin hoops united below and branching out above, where they expand into flattened oval bezels; each bezel carries an inscription.
Gold finger-ring; flat band, broadening from the bottom upwards; slightly raised oval bezel; inscribed: 'Artori Fortun(ati)' (?).
Pale gold finger-ring; flat band, broadening from the bottom upwards; inscribed (the letters are very lightly scratched).
Gold finger-ring; thin flat hoop; long, narrow oval bezel; inscribed.
Gold finger-ring; flat hoop, raised nearly circular bezel; inscribed (in reverse direction): NI.
Silver finger-ring; flat hoop, with two incised lines running along it; the ridge between the two lines rises into a lozenge-shaped bezel; inscribed.
Gold finger-ring; oval sard intaglio: Victory flying to left, holding palm-branch and wreath.
Gold finger-ring; oval box-setting containing a sard in the form of a truncated cone; engraved design: cornucopia.
Gold finger-ring; raised oval bezel with sard intaglio: Jupiter seated to right holding sceptre and patera.
Gold finger-ring; oval bezel with lapis lazuli intaglio: Abraxas in the form of a bearded figure with serpent legs, holding a trident and a peacock; above is the sun, below a crescent moon.
Gold finger-ring; slightly raised oval bezel with convex garnet intaglio: Nemesis winged, pulling forward her chiton with left hand and holding two rods in right hand.
Gold finger-ring; circular bezel with blue paste intaglio: female head to left.

Gold finger-ring; oval bezel with garnet(?) intaglio: grotesque figure wearing peaked cap; he draws a fish out of the water by means of a rod and line held in his right hand; in his left hand he holds a bottle.
Gold finger-ring; convex oval green paste intaglio: Aesculapius with patera and staff entwined with serpent.
Gold finger-ring; oval sard intaglio: two Cupids before a tree; the one stirs the branches with a pole, the other holds a cage (for birds).
Gold finger-ring; bezel consists on an oval box-setting containing a purple convex glass paste intaglio: beardless male portrait head to left.

Gold finger-ring; lozenge-shaped bezel with raised band containing a lozenge-shaped garnet with engraved design: rounded helmet, with knob projecting from above, horns on either side, and two cheek pieces.
Gold finger-ring; sard intaglio: draped figure of Neptune, standing with trident.
Gold finger-ring; oval bezel with paste intaglio: man wearing pointed cap and boar's (?) skin, holding branch before goat which stands on its hind legs.
Gold finger-ring; oval bezel with red jasper intaglio: bird (parrot?) standing to left on branch.
Gold finger-ring; circular red jasper intaglio: sphinx seated to left.
Gold finger-ring; oval plasma intaglio: Athene walking to left; she wears a helmet and carries spear and round shield.
Gold finger-ring; oval bezel with convex sardonyx intaglio: lyre and butterfly; a portion of gold has broken away from the hollow shoulders on either side.
Gold finger-ring; oval sard intaglio: temple of Aphrodite at Paphos with forecourt.
Gold finger-ring; oval bezel with sardonyx intaglio in the form of a truncated cone: ant.
Gold finger-ring; oval bezel with flat nicolo intaglio: head of Herakles, laureate.
Gold finger-ring; oval bezel with amethystine garnet intaglio: Justitia standing with sceptre and scales.
Gold finger-ring; oval sardonyx intaglio: Eros with drapery wrapped around the upper part of his body.
Gold finger-ring; oval bezel with convex sardonyx intaglio: bust of Apollo with bow.
Gold finger-ring; flat oval bezel, in which is inserted a sard intaglio: female head, wearing wreath (the sard is cut into the exact shape of the design).
Gold finger-ring; oval burnt sardonyx in form of a truncated cone; engraved with a dolphin.
Gold finger-ring; flat oval bezel, in which is inserted a sard intaglio: head of Seilenos (the sard is cut into the exact shape of the head).
Gold finger-ring; oval convex plasma intaglio: nude satyr-boy seated on rock, holding out bunch of grapes to goat.
Gold finger-ring; raised oval bezel set with nicolo intaglio: ant.
Gold finger-ring; convex oval garnet within raised band; engraved design: head of Athene to left, helmeted; inscribed on one shoulder.
Gold finger-ring; thick hoop, rounded without and slightly concave within; the bezel is a convex oval with engraved design: griffin walking to left within a dotted border, possibly a forgery.

Pale gold finger-ring; composed of two separate hoops, separated by a beaded wire which is merged into the hoops below; hoops joined together below, and branching out above; each has a flattened oval bezel with engraved designs: scorpion and locust (?).
Gold finger-ring; oval bezel with convex garnet intaglio: winged Nemesis pulling forward chiton and holding scourge.
Gold finger-ring; raised oval bezel set with an imitation onyx cameo in paste: head of an Egyptian goddess(?).

Gold finger-ring; composed of two separate hoops separated by a beaded wire; hoops joined together below, and branching out above; each has a flattened oval bezel with engraved designs: two Egyptian deities.

Pale gold finger-ring; composed of three separate hoops, separated by a plain wire between two twisted wires; hoops are joined together below, and branch out above; each has a flattened oval bezel with engraved design; three Egyptian deities.
Gold finger-ring; composed of three separate hoops, joined together below, and branching out above; each has a flattened oval bezel with engraved design; three Egyptian deities (?).

Pale gold finger-ring; composed of three separate hoops, joined together below, and branching out above; each has a flattened oval bezel with engraved design; (a) terminal deity; (b) Fortuna-Isis; (c) uncertain deity holding out uraeus.
Gold finger-ring; flattened oval bezel with engraved design: palm-branch.
Gold finger-ring; flattened oval bezel with engraved design: left hand plucking lobe of ear with thumb and forefinger.
Gold finger-ring; thin hoop; flattened oval bezel with engraved design: Eros shooting with a bow.
Gold finger-ring; flat hoop; flattened oval bezel with engraved design: Victory standing to left, holding wreath.
Gold finger-ring; flat hoop; flattened oval bezel with engraved design: Fortuna standing to right, with cornucopia and steering oar.
Gold finger-ring; flat hoop; flattened oval bezel with engraved design: Harpokrates(?) behind a column.

Gold finger-ring; flat hoop expanding upwards into a thick convex head with engraved design: temple of Aphrodite at Paphos; pavement indicated by cross-hatched lines, and on either side of the central chamber is a column surmounted by a blazing torch.
Gold finger-ring; flat hoop expanding upwards into a thick convex head with engraved design: front of temple of Aphrodite at Paphos with semicircular forecourt.
Gold finger-ring with a Greek inscription meaning "for the good".
Translucent blue glass finger-ring; oval bezel with design in relief: lion walking to left; above his back, a star.
Gold ear-ring pendant in the form of a winged Eros, both arms bent at the elbows. A suspension-loop is soldered to his back.
Alloy coin.
Ovoid shaped whistle made of tumbaga by lost-wax casting with core. It has two loops for passing a cord at the upper end and a squared hole in the lower half of the body.
Gold ear-ring pendant in the form of a draped Eros flying to front with his arms raised. A suspension-loop is soldered behind.
Alloy coin.

Cast copper alloy spear-butt or ferrule. Hollow circular socket terminating in irregularly flattened basal knob. sharply narrowed at waist in centre.  Irregular opening in waisted portion is unlikely to be original.  Considerable wear on base.
Triangular flat pendant made of gold by lost-wax casting. At the top it has a barrel-shaped tube with grooves at the ends, to pass the cord.
Gold finger-ring; oval bezel with nicolo(?) intaglio: head of Kybele wearing a mural crown; below is a ram running.
Gold finger-ring; oval bezel with convex garnet intaglio: Nemesis standing; before her is a ram running, and two hands clasping ears of corn; inscribed (in reverse direction).
Gold finger-ring; raised oval bezel with garnet intaglio: Bellerophon charging on Pegasus.

Curator's comments: Barbarous imitation of an Augustan coin c.f. RIC1 231 ff. type.
Description: Copper alloy coin; ancient forgery (barbarous imitation).(obverse) Head of Augustus or Tiberius, laureate, left.

Curator's comments: Barbarous imitation of an Augustan coin c.f. RIC1 238a or 245 p.58 type.

Description: Gold finger-ring; composed of two separate hoops joined together below, and branching out above; each has a flattened oval bezel with the same engraved design: female deity or priestess.

Description: Blue glass seal: the youth is shown with a prominent fringe of hair falling across the brow and temple; a long straight nose; small, angular chin; and the broad jaw and cheekbones that were to be such a strong feature of the portraits of Augustus. Beneath him is a cornucopia overflowing with fruit.
Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, bare, right.

Associated names: Named in inscription: Ti Sempronius Graccus
Curator's comments: Augustus reopened the mint of Rome in 18 BC and reconstituted the board of three moneyers (as opposed to the earlier four). This is signified by the reverse legend, where the generic part after the moneyer's name stands for the Latin tres viri "auro argento aere flando feriundo" (AAAFF).
Description: Copper alloy coin.(obverse) Inscription in three lines within oak-wreath.

Curator's comments: The reverse may depict the Curia Julia, the Roman Senate's meeting place in the Forum. Construction was started by Caesar and finished by Augustus, who added the front portico. The dedication took place on 28 August 29 BC.
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Octavian, bare, right.

Curator's comments: The reverse depicts the triumphal arch awarded to Octavian in 29 B.C. for his victory, over Antony and Cleopatra at the Battle of Actium, 2 September 31 B.C. Like the later arch which commemorated his recovery of the Roman standards from the Parthians, this arch stood in close proximity to the Temple of Divus Julius at the southern entrance to the Roman Forum.
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Octavian, bare, right.

Curator's comments: The reverse depicts the triumphal arch awarded to Octavian in 29 B.C. for his victory, over Antony and Cleopatra at the Battle of Actium, 2 September 31 B.C. Like the later arch which commemorated his recovery of the Roman standards from the Parthians, this arch stood in close proximity to the Temple of Divus Julius at the southern entrance to the Roman Forum.

Description: Pottery: base of a coarseware jar with round impressed name-stamp on underside: MARCUSI(reversed).
Seal. Rectangular seal of black onyx (?) with a circular stem; face engraved with an composite animal having an elephant torso and fish tail; taurine above.
Bronze figure of the principal horse from a chariot team.
Bronze forceps with fine-toothed jaws, perhaps used as a "uvula crusher".
Terracotta figure of gladiators.
Pottery: base of a coarseware jar with round impressed name-stamp on underside: OFE(?)SEVV.
Dull green blown glass bottle with handle and spout, and a tubular pushed-in base-ring with a pontil mark.
Bronze needle with bent eye. Thin bronze wire with circular section, diminishing toward the point. No patina.
Marble portrait head of Gaius Caesar, Augustus' grandson.

Curator's comments: The exact meaning of CA on this coinage is not known. RPC suggests that C(aesar) A(ugustus) is perhaps the best explanation, although some believe that CA is a representation of honorific wreaths to Augustus by the C(ommune) A(siae).

Curator's comments: Augustus reopened the mint of Rome in 18 BC and reconstituted the board of three moneyers (as opposed to the earlier four). This is signified by the reverse legend, where the generic part after the moneyer's name stands for the Latin tres viri "auro argento aere flando feriundo" (AAAFF).

Curator's comments: In 20 BC, Augustus scored a diplomatic coup by recovering the legionary eagles and standards (SIGNIS) which had been lost to the Parthians by Crassus in 53 BC, thereby erasing the stain of that earlier military disaster. The treaty also provided for the return of surviving Roman captives, who had been in Parthian hands for 33 years.
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, bare, right.

Curator's comments: This coin is considered to refer to the dangerous illness which afflicted Augustus when at Tarragona, in Spain, and the public vows made for his restoration and safe return.

Curator's comments: This coin type refers to the extensive measures taken by Augustus to improve the road system in Italy. The depiction on reverse may be that of the Milvian Bridge which carried the Via Flaminia, Italy's great nothern highway, across the Tiber just north of Rome. The historian Dio Cassius records the erection of "statues on arches on the bridge over the Tiber" in commemoration of the emperor's munificence in personally financing the work carried out on the Via Flaminia.
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, bare, left.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'QVOD. VIAE. MVN. SVNT.', u'Inscription Position': u'reverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: In 44 BC, following the death of Julius Caesar, a comet appeared in the heavens over Rome and was accepted to be a manifestation of the divine soul of Julius Caesar. It was thought to herald a new age of peace and prosperity. Augustus used this event to emphasize his familial association with the deified Julius.
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, wearing oak-wreath, left.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'CAESAR  AVGVSTVS', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'anti-clockwise', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: The cippus, set up in Rome's Regio VII, records Augustus' generosity in making special contributions to the public treasury in order to help finance the restoration of the public roads. Work on the Via Flaminia was undertaken entirely at his expense, as it was necessary to make the route suitable for the frequent passage of armies.
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Equestrian statue of Augustus right, on inscribed pedestal, in front of city walls and gate.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'L.VINICIVS L.F.III.VIR', u'Inscription Position': u'reverse', u'Inscription Comment': u'clockwise', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}, {u'Inscription Content': u'S.P.Q.R IMP CAES', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'on pedestal', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: Augustus reopened the mint of Rome in 18 BC and reconstituted the board of three moneyers (as opposed to the earlier four). This is signified by the reverse legend, where the generic part after the moneyer's name stands for the Latin tres viri "auro argento aere flando feriundo" (AAAFF).

Associated names: Named in inscription & portrayed: Gaius Caesar
Curator's comments: The reverse illustrates the dynastic and political position of Gaius and Lucius at this time. The brothers were the sons of Agrippa and Julia, daughter of Augustus. They were due to succeed Augustus but predeceased him in AD 4 and 2 respectively. The shields and spears represent the coming of age of Gaius and Lucius and the honour of princepes iuventutis, "first among the youth" which was an honour bestowed upon them by Augustus. The simpulum represents Gaius who became a pontiff in 7 BC. The lituus or augural staff was the symbol for the college of augurs and refers to Lucius, who was appointed as augur. This type has been identified as the "Tribute Penny" of the bible (although this is unlikely given its manufacture in the western part of the empire).
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, laureate, right.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'CAESAR AVGVSTVS DIVI F PATER PATRIAE', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'anti-clockwise', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}, {u'Inscription Content': u'C L CAESARES', u'Inscription Position': u'reverse exergue', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: In the Res Gestae, Augustus records that the Senate, in giving him the title Augustus, also decreed that the doorposts of his house be officially decorated with laurel, that the corona civica be placed over the door and that a shield be displayed in the Curia Iulia. This shield, or clipeus, had been dedicated to him by the Senate and the Roman People on account of his virtues of bravery, clemency, justice, and piety; virtues which were inscribed on the shield itself. The return in 19 BC of the Roman standards captured by the Parthians in earlier conflicts offered an excellent opportunity to once again recall Augustus' pietas, one of the virtues recorded on the clipeus.
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, bare, right.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'[CL.V]', u'Inscription Position': u'reverse', u'Inscription Comment': u'on shield, no longer visible', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}, {u'Inscription Content': u'CAESAR AVGVSTVS', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'anti-clockwise', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Associated names: Named in inscription & portrayed: Gaius Caesar
Curator's comments: The reverse illustrates the dynastic and political position of Gaius and Lucius at this time. The brothers were the sons of Agrippa and Julia, daughter of Augustus. They were due to succeed Augustus but predeceased him in AD 4 and 2 respectively. The shields and spears represent the coming of age of Gaius and Lucius and the honour of princepes iuventutis, "first among the youth" which was an honour bestowed upon them by Augustus. The simpulum represents Gaius who became a pontiff in 7 BC. The lituus or augural staff was the symbol for the college of augurs and refers to Lucius, who was appointed as augur. This type has been identified as the "Tribute Penny" of the bible (although this is unlikely given its manufacture in the western part of the empire).
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, laureate, right.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'CAESAR AVGVSTVS DIVI F PATER PATRIAE', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}, {u'Inscription Content': u'C L CAESARES', u'Inscription Position': u'reverse exergue', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Associated names: Named in inscription & portrayed: Gaius Caesar
Curator's comments: The reverse illustrates the dynastic and political position of Gaius and Lucius at this time. The brothers were the sons of Agrippa and Julia, daughter of Augustus. They were due to succeed Augustus but predeceased him in AD 4 and 2 respectively. The shields and spears represent the coming of age of Gaius and Lucius and the honour of princepes iuventutis, "first among the youth" which was an honour bestowed upon them by Augustus. The simpulum represents Gaius who became a pontiff in 7 BC. The lituus or augural staff was the symbol for the college of augurs and refers to Lucius, who was appointed as augur. This type may possibly be the "Tribute Penny" of the bible (although this is unlikely given its manufacture in the western part of the empire).
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, laureate, right.

Curator's comments: Roman Pottery
Description: Pottery skyphos with ring-handles (one missing), decorated with an ivy-wreath and berries each side; red-brown fabric with iridescent green glaze on the exterior, honey-brown glaze on the interior. 3 firing tripod scars on interior of base.
Alloy coin.

Curator's comments: The foot, catch plate and bow of La Tène III brooches were cast as a single piece.
Description: Copper alloy brooch of nauhem (La Tène III) type. Flat, triangular bow with incised decoration, four-coil spring with internal chord, and framed catchplate. Very good condition, pin also survives.

Large copper alloy bowl.  Shape a flattened hemisphere with everted rim.  Circular concavity in base, centrally pierced by a small, circular hole.  Remains of a poorly-incised triquetra, enclosed by a double circle, discernible within this hollow.  Indistinct traces of compass-drawn curves on interior surface of base. Possible hammer-marks on both surfaces.

Iron spear-head. Slender, leaf-shaped blade, lozenge-shaped in cross-section.  Areas of haphazard, rocked-graver lines at the base of the blade on each face give a rough matted effect, but these are scarcely visible to the naked eye.  The hammered, round-sectioned socket is open along the vertical seam.  Two transverse iron rivets pierce the lower end; each projects slightly from the surface of the socket.

Gold finger-ring with a Greek alphabetic inscription incised on the bezel; hammered from a single piece of metal; the hoop is a simple band which widens to a horse-shoe shaped bezel; the three Greek characters (ΖΟΗ, 'Life') are arranged in a triangle, with the letter eta (Η) flanked by stylised trees.

Hollow gold ear-ring, in the form of Eros holding a phiale in one hand and in the other an oblong plaque stamped with a bee (?). A cross-band is engraved between his breasts. The figure is suspended from a hook masked by a disc, on which is a rosette of seven filigree petals, once inlaid with blue enamel.

Hollow gold ear-ring, in the form of Eros holding a phiale in one hand and in the other an oblong plaque stamped with a bee (?). A cross-band is engraved between his breasts. The figure is suspended from a hook masked by a disc, on which is a rosette of seven filigree petals, once inlaid with blue enamel.

Ear-ring pendant of thin gold, stamped with a draped Eros (?) to front, head to left, with his right hand outstretched and his left arm raised and bent at the elbow. On his head are two feathers (?); above is an almost circular plate stamped with an ox-head to front, and a border of dots. Behind the ox-head are traces of a hook attachment.

Gold finger-ring; composed of two separate hoops; upper parts of the rings are separated by two twisted wired, the extremities of which have a pellet soldered to them; hoops joined together below, and branching out above; each has a flattened oval bezel with engraved designs: two female Egyptian deities.

Gold finger-ring; composed of thin wire twisted into spiral of nine turns; one ends terminates in serpent's head, the other in its tail; between the head and tail is soldered a 'nodus Herculeus' and on the other side is attached a plaited wire, with a small disc at either end.

Gold finger-ring; ring formed of two hoops, convex without and concave within; soldered side by side; they are separated from one another by two beaded wires; to the head of either is attached an oval box-setting which contained a stone or paste now missing.
Gold finger-ring; large oval bezel with sard intaglio: bust of Jupiter(?) to front with drapery over his shoulder; he holds up a thunderbolt(?); inscribed (in reverse direction) VRIDOL|ANOS.

Gold finger-ring; composed of four separate hoops, joined together below, and branching out above; each has a flattened oval bezel with engraved design, apparently representing Egyptian deities, but only Anubis can be distinguished; the bezels were originally soldered together.
Gold finger-ring; flat hoop; flattened oval bezel with engraved design: Aphrodite standing to front wringing her hair; on her right is Eros, on her left a laver with a dove perched upon it.

Cast copper alloy spear-butt or ferrule. Hollow circular socket terminating in basal knob of flattened-spherical form. Waisted central portion, and convex moulding near the top. The edges of the socket moulding and the upper portion of the basal knob are defined by a reserved, hyphenated line. There is also a faint, incised line around the mouth of the socket. Two opposed circular rivet holes in the socket moulding. Base worn. Almost identical to 1870,1227.2.

Cast copper alloy spear-butt or ferrule. Hollow circular socket terminating in basal knob of flattened-spherical form. Waisted central portion, and convex moulding near the top. Circular motif on base, with slightly raised centre. Mouth, socket moulding and upper portion of knob defined by incised lines. Wear on base.

Cast copper alloy spear-butt or ferrule. Hollow circular socket terminating in hemispherical basal knob. Waisted central portion, and convex moulding near the top. Edges of mouth, socket-moulding and upper portion of knob defined by lightly-incised lines.  Two opposed circular holes in socket-moulding. Wear on base.

Curator's comments: The youthful head on the reverse has usually been interpreted as that of a rejuvenated Caesar, on the evidence of the comet ("sidus Iulium") which surmounts the portrait. However, there is clearly no resemblance to the late dictator and it seems more satisfactory to regard it is a personification of the "New Age" itself, endowed, like so many of the divine images of Augustus' reign, with the features of the emperor

Description: Silver snake finger-ring: this intact two-headed snake ring is an unusual type, with the heads almost meeting at the top. The scales are carefully engraved, with those on the upper part of the snakes' bodies small and overlapping, and those underneath broad and ribbed. The heads are  particularly fierce in appearance, with the mouths opened to reveal a strip of metal forming the tongue. The beady eyes are placed beneath a heavy hood of skin, and are picked out with tiny cornelian stones.

Curator's comments: This denarius celebrates the successful conclusion of Octavian's Egyptian campaign. The conquest the Ptolemaic kingdom of Egypt in August 30BC removed the last obstacle to Octavian's achievement of supreme power in the Roman world. In 29 BC, Octavian returned to Rome for his official triumph (a triple one, primarily celebrating his successes at Actium and Alexandria but also in Illyricum) and in the following year this coin picturing a crocodile with the inscription AEGVPTO CAPTA celebrated the event.
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Augustus, bare, right; below, capricorn right.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'AEGVPTO CAPTA', u'Inscription Position': u'reverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'above and below', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Curator's comments: Augustus reopened the mint of Rome in 18 BC and reconstituted the board of three moneyers (as opposed to the earlier four). This is signified by the reverse legend, where the generic part after the moneyer's name stands for the Latin tres viri "auro argento aere flando feriundo" (AAAFF).

Curator's comments: The monument depicted on the coin is a statue of Octavian on a column decorated with prows (rostra) of enemy ships. The monument was erected in the Roman Forum to commemorate the naval victory over Sextus Pompeius. Thus, the column, and by extension the image on the coin, likened the civil war victory to one over a foreign enemy.

Curator's comments: The monument depicted on the coin is a statue of Octavian, nude, on a column decorated with prows (rostra) of enemy ships. The monument was erected in the Roman Forum to commemorate the naval victory over Sextus Pompeius. Thus, the column, and by extension the image on the coin, likened the civil war victory to one over a foreign enemy.
Description: Silver coin; pierced for suspension.(obverse) Head of Octavian, laureate, right.

Curator's comments: This coin type was part of the large issues of Octavian in celebration of his victory over Antony at Actium, Sept 2, 31BC. The reverse type on this particular issue is especially notable, being a direct reference to the naval battle.
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Bust of Victory right, wings spread.

Curator's comments: This coin type was part of Octavian's pre-Actium coinage, issued in response to Antony's legionary series. This type emphasizes Octavian's legitimacy as Caesar's heir, through divine power (Venus is the guardian deity of Caesar and the Julia gens) and military prowess (the reverse depiction of Octavian as a military leader).
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Bust of Pax right, draped and wearing stephane; behind, cornucopia; before, olive-branch.

Curator's comments: This denarius celebrates the successful conclusion of Octavian's Egyptian campaign. The conquest the Ptolemaic kingdom of Egypt in August 30BC removed the last obstacle to Octavian's achievement of supreme power in the Roman world. In 29 BC, Octavian returned to Rome for his official triumph (a triple one, primarily celebrating his successes at Actium and Alexandria but also in Illyricum) and in the following year this coin picturing a crocodile with the inscription AEGVPTO CAPTA celebrated the event.
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Octavian, bare, right; behind, lituus.

The legend ASIA RECEPTA when translated states, "Asia recovered" and refers to the fact that Octavian regained the Asian provinces and client states for the Roman Empire.

Description: A slab of white marble, the top and right hand bottom corner broken away with a fifty five line inscription, in Greek. There are twelve lines missing.  The subject of the inscription is probably a copy of a joint decree issued by the Asiatic Greeks, in which they welcomed or honoured Gaius Caesar, the adopted son of the emperor Augustus, and which appropriately commenced by praising the emperor who sent him.

Description: Oval fired clay token; low relief designs on both sides: obverse, full-face head of Sarapis; reverse, head of a bearded elderly man in profile to right; chipped; very worn.
Circular fired clay token; low relief design on both sides of  two seated figures wearing high poloi hats, reclining on a couch with lettering around them; worn; abraded; chipped.

Circular fired clay token; low relief design on obverse of a portrait bust of a figure wearing a high polos hat, facing frontally, on either side of the bust are traces of star or rosette motifs; on the reverse is an unclear scratched mark; worn; abraded; chipped.

Rectangular dark fired clay token; with traces of red paint; hole pierced through centre; low relief designs on both sides of a pair of seated figures wearing high poloi hats, reclining on a couch, with lettering around them; worn; abraded; chipped.
Circular fired clay token; low relief designs on both sides; on obverse - vessel/vase; reverse - unclear; worn; chipped; abraded.
Irregularly shaped fired clay token; low relief designs on both sides of a seated figure wearing a high polos hat, reclining on a couch, with lettering around them; badly chipped; worn.
Circular fired clay token; low relief designs on both sides: obverse, impression of a dove and/or head of Isis; reverse, a date-palm branch; chipped; abraded.

Circular fired clay token; low relief designs on both sides; on obverse side of uncertain circular object (possibly a shield), enclosed in a wreath, design on reverse side is of a nude figure; chipped; very worn; abraded.

Circular fired clay token; low relief designs on both sides; on obverse - figure of man (king?) wearing high crown/ polos hat and seated on a stool, on reverse - recumbent zebu; chipped; very worn; abraded.

Rectangular fired clay token; low relief designs on both sides, on obverse - a portrait bust of a figure wearing a high polos hat, facing frontally, with lettering around them; on reverse - circular object (possibly shield in a wreath), design unintelligible; chipped; worn; abraded.

Rectangular or oval fired clay token; traces of red paint; low relief designs on both sides; obverse, draped female seated on stool facing left and inscription; reverse, reclining figure, possibly on couch; chipped; worn; abraded.
Rectangular fired clay token; low relief inscription on both sides; chipped; abraded.
