Description: Finger-ring; cast copper alloy; hoop narrow at the back and expanding to the shoulders; oval bezel, much worn, engraved in intaglio with two confronted birds, above and below which are Karoshti inscriptions.
Cast copper alloy terret, oval, of oval section with 3 winged knobs and bar of flat section between moulded ribs.

Curator's comments: Re-used.
Description: Corroded copper alloy coin pierced near edge for suspension.

Green blown glass flask with a plain cut rim, a cylindrical neck, a globular body, two flat three-reeded handles, and a flattened base with a coil base-ring with no pontil mark. Decorated with a pincered coil on the centre of the neck, and bands of wheel-cut lines.

Finger-ring; cast copper alloy; oval bezel, with part of the hoop preserved; engraved in intagio with a man standing to the right, wearing a sword, and holding up a wreath in his right hand; on either side, a Karoshti inscription written vertically.

Curator's comments: Document: Impression on an envelope, OA archive.
Description: Oval seal in cornelian with a flat face and slightly convex back; engraved with a standing nude male holding a spear; single Brāhmī letter, apparently added at a later date.
Silver coin.(obverse) Beardless male head, laureate, resembling Augustus, right; wreath border tied below.
Gold ear-ring, S-shaped hook with a ribbed bar soldered horizontally to the end; above the bar is a pearl bead on a wire (missing in one case); from the bar are two pearl beads on ribbed wire rods.
Gold ear-ring, S-shaped hook with a ribbed bar soldered horizontally to the end; above the bar is a pearl bead on a wire (missing in one case); from the bar are two pearl beads on ribbed wire rods.
Two upper parts of gold finger-rings joined to form a loop. The bezels are engraved with heads of a cupid and a satyr.
Gold finger-ring set with a sardonyx cameo engraved with a head of Medusa with wings in her hair and snaky locks.

Curator's comments: Christy collection registration slip description, written in 1894?:
Description: Boomerang made of wood.
Silver ring: engraved on the bezel are the goddess Cybele and a youth, perhaps Attis.

Gold ear-ring: plain ring with a hook at one end and a loop at the other; on it are five pendants: a plain gold bead, a pearl on a pendant rod, a cross within a wheel, a green glass bead on a rod, and a double ring of beads.

Gold ear-ring: ring with a spirally twisted wire around it, ending in a bull's head with a loop soldered below for the reception of the other end; the neck is decorated with a green glass bead between two pearls, separated from each other by small gold beaded rings.

Gold ear-ring, two intertwisted wires ending in a dolphin's head, with a cylindrical dark glass bead at the neck. There are two rings below the head, and one at the end of the wire; the fastening pin between them is missing.

Gold ear-ring: plain gold semicircle with a hook at one end and a dolphin's head at the other, with a globule in its mouth and a loop for the hook soldered beneath the mouth. A wire is soldered into the head, on which are strung three gold beads and four gold rings composed of globules.

Gold finger-ring; composed of five thin wire rings bound together by a broad band below and two thin bands at the sides; to the head is soldered a relief figure embossed in thin gold (? Actaeon attacked by a hound).
Gold finger-ring; broad hoop, rounded without and expanding upwards; flattened circular bezel, to which is soldered a relief crescent with a raised pellet at the middle and at either extremity.
Transparent green glass bezel broken from a ring; of large oval form with engraved design upon it of a shrine with three cross-shaped acroteria.
Iron finger-ring; oval sard intaglio: eagle on thunderbolt upon a vase; on the right are two cocks on a cornucopia.
Iron finger-ring; oval bezel with yellow paste intaglio: Victory to left on ship's prow, holding out wreath.

Gold finger-ring; broad plain hoop, convex without, with open rounded ends; to these is soldered a bust of Serapis in relief (unwrought behind), across the direction of the hoop; he is draped and wears a modius.
Chalcedony finger-ring; inserted in the flattened oval bezel is a convex circular dark blue paste, on which are four round spots of white with centres of blue.
Iron finger-ring; oval bezel with sard intaglio: draped priest standing to right, holding staff with cruciform end in right hand and patera in left.
Iron finger-ring; oval raised red jasper intaglio, partly broken away; head of a bearded man wearing a fillet in profile to left.
Iron finger-ring; large oval bezel containing a convex light green paste with design in relief: Cupid and Psyche embracing.
Iron finger-ring; oval bezel with red jasper intaglio: horse standing to left, grazing; beneath the bezel is a small oval hole.
Bronze finger-ring; oval bezel with paste intaglio: Serapis standing to front, holding patera and cornucopia; lower part of hoop broken away.
Bronze finger-ring; oval bezel with female bust in high relief, wearing hood over back of head and chiton with v-shaped opening in front; gilded.
Bronze finger-ring; oval bezel containing a convex pale green glass paste with engraved design: draped female figure standing to right with spear or staff in her right hand; remains of gilding.
Bronze finger-ring; bezel contains a slightly convex green paste with intaglio design: draped female figure standing to right, with her right arm on a column.

Bronze finger-ring; bezel contains a strongly convex dark red paste with intaglio design: draped female figure leaning her right arm on a column and holding palm-branches in either hand; traces of gilding.
Bronze finger-ring; oval bezel contains a convex dark red paste intaglio: draped female figure standing to right; she rests her right arm on a column and holds out a phiale with her left.
Gold finger-ring; plain hoop, rounded without, flat within; it expands upwards; oval bezel containing a paste imitating a nicolo.
Gold finger-ring; hollow hoop, rounded without, flat within; oval bezel with convex garnet in raised gold setting.
Gold-plated bronze finger-ring; large circular bezel (partly broken away) with design in relief: bust of Apollo(?) to front, with locks streaming away in all directions.
Gold finger-ring; oval bezel with onyx cameo: Mercury standing to left, holding purse in right and caduceus in left hand.

Gold finger-ring; long pointed oval bezel set with convex garnet intaglio: Fortuna standing, with cornucopia on arm, and hand resting on a steering oar(?) which has the appearance of a long staff with crook at the end.

Gold finger-ring; the bezel is in the form of a long oval box-setting which contains a dark red glass paste intaglio: tall draped female figure holding a staff in her left hand and some object in her right hand.
Gold finger-ring; on the oval bezel is a raised triangle, within which is an oval setting containing a convex garnet intaglio: Tyche to left, holding cornucopia.
Gold finger-ring; broad, nearly flat hoop; convex pointed oval bezel with a convex dark paste intaglio: Nike walking and holding a wreath.
Gold finger-ring; the ring is in two coils and terminates in two relief busts of Isis, one wearing a calathos, the other two feathers.
Gold finger-ring; high hoop, rounded without and rising into oval bezel with design in relief: Leda and the swan; imitation-plaited wire border.
Gold finger-ring; broad hoop; large circular bezel with engraved design: Osiris seated, with Isis on the left and Nephthys on right.
Gold finger-ring set with a nicolo seal engraved with Helios wearing a radiated crown and chlamys, holding a whip; before him is a burning altar; in the field are a crescent and a star.
Gold finger-ring; plain rounded hoop, with flattened oval bezel; bust of Serapis, draped and wearing modius, in relief, attached to hoop.
Gold finger-ring; broad hoop; large circular bezel with engraved design: Isis, wearing disc and horns and carrying uraeus, stands before a bust of Osiris-Canopus set upon a low stool; exergual line.
Gold finger-ring; thin hoop, oval bezel with engraved design: Eros standing and reading from a roll which he holds up with both hands.
Limestone finger-ring; upon the oval bezel is a carved rectangle which rises in three receding tiers; one side of the bezel considerably damaged.
Glass finger-ring; oval bezel filled with a convex piece of glass, opaque and iridescent; hoop is pale green and translucent.
Gold-plated bronze finger-ring; oval bezel containing a convex garnet; engraved design: Eros running, with long palm-branch(?) over his shoulder.
Black jasper gem engraved with a slightly bearded portrait-head in profile, wearing a fillet, probably a tributary king of the time of Augustus; there is a Greek inscription.
Red jasper gem engraved with a grotesque mask in profile conjoined with bird's legs and tail.

Translucent green glass finger-ring; floor of bezel has draped female figure painted upon it; the face and arm are painted white; the drapery is grey with brown borders; round the figure is a rim of white; the painting is covered with an oval plate of translucent glass.
Sard gem engraved with a Kybele riding on a lion at full speed, looking back; she wears a fillet (?) and chiton, and holds a sceptre.
Sard gem engraved with Eros holding a caduceus and a spear; behind him is the club of Herakles.
Nicolo gem engraved with a half-draped Aphrodite (Venus Victrix) wearing a fillet; she holds a helmet and spear, and rests her arm on a column; at her feet is an uncertain object.
Convex plasma gem engraved with Ares seated on a rock, wearing a helmet and holding a shield and a trophy.

Curator's comments: Hellenizing style.
Description: Sealstone of opaque dark green glass paste with dark blue and white bands, engraved with a nude man and woman conversing, perhaps Achilles and Thetis.
Gem of glass paste imitating nicolo, set in a silver finger-ring, engraved with Eros running to the right beside a chariot with two galloping horses.
Sard gem engraved with the Ephesian Artemis wearing a calathos, her arms held out each side and resting on the supports of a throne (?) with cross-pieces at intervals. At her feet are two animals.
Copper alloy coin: procurator of Judea - Coponius.
Gem of glass paste imitating sard, engraved with two Erotes in a sailing-boat; one adjusts the sail and the other leans over the prow, lifting a third Eros out of the water.

Gold ear-ring: two intertwisted wires ending in a dolphin's head, with a loop soldered below for the reception of the other end; behind the head are strung a rounded emerald bead, a hollow gold bead, and a cylindrical banded agate bead, separated by four rings decorated with globules.

Curator's comments: Theban type (Arlt 2011)
Description: Maerua wood mummy-label of Hieros, son of Psenmonthes.

Curator's comments: Theban type (Arlt 2011)
Description: Maerua wood mummy-label of Psenosorbouchis, son of Pamonthes.

Gold ear-ring, two intertwisted wires ending in a dolphin's head, with a cylindrical dark glass bead at the neck. There are two rings below the head, and one at the end of the wire; the fastening pin between them is missing.

Curator's comments: Roman Pottery
Description: Clay stamp for decorating pottery.
Dark green glass finger-ring; flattened oval pointed bezel with mask of  Medusa in relief in opaque yellow glass.
Buff sandstone cylindrical spindle whorl, with cylindrical hole and three lines round side.
Plano-convex sandstone spindle whorl; with 4 lines round and a circular groove at base, cylindrical perforation.
Inscribed marble altar dedicated to Gaius and Lucius Caesar, the grandsons of Augustus. Each prince is described as the leader of Roman youth, an honour given them in 6 and in 3 BC.
Dark green glass finger-ring; flattened oval pointed bezel with mask of Medusa in relief in opaque white glass.
Translucent blue glass pendant in the form of a seated goddess flanked by two lions(?).
One of five gold bracteate discs; impression of coin; head of Antiochus I(?) within beaded border; before him is a sceptre (?).

Pottery handled bowl: black burnished; high, rounded body; incised ladder-pattern chevrons round the girth bounded above and below by line of stamped ĕshapes between grooves; faceted upstanding rim; small looped handle; hand-made.
Gold brooch; convex disk, backed with flat plate; bordered with beaded wire; front of plate set with oval plasma surrounded by four smaller plasmas; on the back a hinged pin and catch.

Gold twisted bracelet; three hollow gold strands twisted spirally over plain gold wire of square section; ends merge into a single gold wire which twists into a spiral around the ends of the bracelet.
One of a pair of gold bracelets; plain gold rod of penannular form; ending in head of cubical form, in one case partially broken away; hollow.

Gold pendant; three small discs; border of plain and beaded wires soldered together (bunch of grapes?); middle circular setting filled with enamel (?) or paste (?); loop for suspension; small rosette of eight petals has been soldered on.
One of a pair of gold bracelets; composed of two penannular tubes soldered side by side; between them a rod of triangular section; end of each tube terminates in a berry composed of globules.
Pair of gold tubes; network of wire circles with globules soldered at point of contact; in middle hollow gold tube, capped at both ends; piece of jewellery.
Gold amulet; cylinder with cap at one end, cap missing from other; filled with sulphur; ribbed ring for suspension; triangle of globules soldered beneath; ornamented with three lines of globules.

Curator's comments: Threads played an important part in magic.
Description: Gold amulet-pendant; hollow cylinder with fitted cap at one end; three rings soldered for suspension; each decorated with three globules; cylinder fitted with sulphur; according to the catalogue when the sulphur is removed, at the end is a mass of white silk thread, originally twisted up into a strand;

Gold pendant; crescent shaped, ending in a globule at either side; suspended by loop of ribbed ribbon; beneath which is a globule; from a loop (masked by a rosette) in the middle of the crescent is suspended a second crescent; ending at each side in a pyramid of globules surmounted by a rosette; in the middle is a sitting male figure holding something across his knees; surrounded by acanthus tendrils.

Gold pendant; crescent; pyramid globules at either end; surmounted by rosette of.eight petals; crescent is filled in with a convex disk; decorated in the middle with a rosette of eight petals surrounded with tendrils in filigree; this is bordered with circles of plain and twisted wires; the ribbed suspending loop at the top of the crescent is masked by a double rosette; back is closed in with a plain sheet of gold.

Gold pendant; crescent; globule above pyramid, ribbed loop below; convex disc surmounted by rosette of four pointed leaves in beaded filigree; bordered by plaited and beaded wires; back of disc hollow and not closed.

Gold pendant; crescent with solid pyramid globules at either end (right end broken away); disc surmounted by large rosette of eleven filigree petals; surrounded by border of plain and twisted wires; plain suspending loop with globule underneath.

Gold pendant; thin crescent with globule at either end; convex disc with rosette of ten filigree petals; surrounded by circles of twisted and plain wires; plain suspending loop, masked by a rosette of nine petals; back open.
Gold embossed disc; stamped with figure of flying eagle; border of beaded wire between two plain wires soldered round edge of disc; piece of jewellery

Gold disc; stamped with design of three draped figures standing to the front on a platform; border consisting of beaded wire between two plain wires; at back two small rings (originally three); piece of jewellery.
Gold bracteate disc; stamped over coin of Kolophon; Homer seated to left on throne; inscription runs vertically in front of figure.
One of five gold bracteate discs; impression of coin; head of Antiochus I(?) within beaded border; before him is a sceptre (?).
One of five gold bracteate discs; impression of coin; head of Antiochus I(?) within beaded border; before him is a sceptre (?).
Gold bracteate disc; with impression of Roman Republican coin; head of Ceres to l. wearing a wreath of corn; inscribed in field behind head.
Gold finger-ring of standard early type.  The shoulders are hollow, and the setting is a small oval nicolo (quartz), engraved with a figure of Bonus Eventus carrying grapes and a hare.
Two gold clasps from the end of a necklace linked together, consisting each of a leaf shaped ornament ending on one side in a loop and on the other in a hook and ring respectively.
Gold jewellery element curved gold rod; hollow; ending in a loop, probably from a necklace; apparently a hook was originally attached to a similar rod and inserted into the loop.
Gold link of a chain, with a loop at one end, the join of which is masked by a small rosette and a globule at the other; the join of the loop is masked by a large globule.
One of a pair of gold bracelets; composed of two penannular tubes soldered side by side; between them a rod of triangular section; end of each tube terminates in a berry composed of globules.

Curator's comments: Portrait of Augustus in the Prima Porta type. Most of the bust restored.
Description: Marble portrait bust of Augustus.
Part of a gold necklace composed of gold links in the form of a rod with a loop at each end, cylindrical green glass beads strung between the loops.

One of three gold pendants; consisting each of a ring soldered to a disc; the latter stamped with a flower of nine petals; in the ring is inserted a second ring from which hang four pendants suspended from chains of two links; the pendants are shell-shaped; a boss in the middle of one side; a beaded border round the bottom.
One of five gold bracteate discs; impression of coin; head of Antiochus I(?) within beaded border; before him is a sceptre (?).

Part of a gold oval box (?); decorated with triangles of globules; with apices pointing alternately upwards and downwards, the ends are open, possibly having been broken away; one face of box impressed with a palmette on a capital with volutes; other face filigree with globules; possibly designed to represent column of temple and its semicircular forecourt.

One of three gold pendants; ring soldered to disc; second ring inserted from which hang four pendants suspended on a chain of two links; pendants shell shaped; boss in middle; beaded border; stamped with nine petals.
One of five gold bracteate discs; impression of coin; head of Antiochus I(?) within beaded border; before him is a sceptre (?).
Copper alloy finger-ring in the form of a snake wound in two complete spirals; head projecting from one side and tail (now broken) from other; incised with herringbone pattern.

Fragment of a flat terracotta mould for making appliqués for decorating Arretine wares.  Impressions of six similar tragic masks in three rows, with hair nearly incised over the forehead and falling in straight curls down the sides of the face.  Wears fillet.
Copper alloy coin.(obverse) Head of Silenus, facing; before, amphora pouring.

Gold finger-ring; in the form of coiled serpent with overlapping head and tail terminals; rounded exterior, flat interior; head and tail taper to points, and are decorated with incised lines and cross-hatching.

Curator's comments: Walker & Higgs 2001
Description: Parian marble portrait head from a statue of a Roman.

Copper alloy strap-union. Two rectangular strap loops (for straps up to 15mm wide) are placed under a cruciform decorative mount. The mount is centred on an openwork quatrefoil arrangement. This central square contains four diagonal pointed ovals, each decorated in relief with a central rib flanked by zigzag lines. Four arms project from the central square, set at 90 degrees.  Two of the opposing arms are rectangular in shape and decorated with relief scrolls reserved against a background of red glass of which only a trace remains. The other arms are curved, with petal-shaped heads. Each is decorated with a palmette motif flanked by two circles all reserved against a background of red glass, of which one fragment remains. The designs on all of the arms are based on palmette and lyre motifs.  The cells to be inlaid with glass were prepared in the clay mould before casting.

Curator's comments: Vila llonch 2013
Description: Nose-ornament in the shape of a stylised human face made of tumbaga by hammering and cutting. It is composed of several sheet pieces joined by wire staples; the surface is gold enriched. Given its large size, it would have functioned almost as a mask covering a good part of the wearer's face.

Curator's comments: This finger-ring is from a series of similar rings, made of bronze, silver or gold, comes this simple example.
Description: Gold finger-ring.

Curator's comments: This head once formed part of a statue of the Roman Emperor Augustus (ruled 27 BC-AD 14).
Description: Bronze head from an over-life-sized statue of Augustus: the head is broken through the neck but is otherwise in an excellent state of preservation.  There are four fragments of plaster from the head. The eyes are inlaid, with glass pupils set in metal rings, the irises of calcite. The eyebrows are plastically rendered. The emperor's head is turned to his right, with the pronounced twist to the neck typical of Hellenistic work. The hair falls on the brow in the divided and curving cut that marked most of Augustus's portraits as emperor.  The facial planes are broad. The mouth is slightly downturned, a feature of late Hellenistic portraiture. The ears project markedly, the upper lobes bending forwards.
Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Octavian right, bearded; around, inscription. Border of dots.

Curator's comments: This coin type was part of Octavian's pre-Actium coinage, issued in response to Antony's legionary series. This type emphasizes Octavian's legitimacy as Caesar's heir, through divine power (Venus is the guardian deity of Caesar and the Julia gens) and military prowess (the reverse depiction of Octavian as a military leader).
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Bust of Pax right, draped and wearing stephane; behind, cornucopia; before, olive-branch.

Curator's comments: This denarius celebrates the successful conclusion of Octavian's Egyptian campaign. The conquest the Ptolemaic kingdom of Egypt in August 30BC removed the last obstacle to Octavian's achievement of supreme power in the Roman world. In 29 BC, Octavian returned to Rome for his official triumph (a triple one, primarily celebrating his successes at Actium and Alexandria but also in Illyricum) and in the following year this coin picturing a crocodile with the inscription AEGVPTO CAPTA celebrated the event.In Bibliothèque National de France’s catalogue (BNCMER Auguste) mint attributed to Ephesus.
Description: Silver coin.(obverse) Head of Octavian, bare, left; behind, lituus.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'CAESAR [COS VI]', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Comment': u'anti-clockwise', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Description: Marble head from a statue of Octavian: in the style of a Hellenistic prince. The lower edge of the neck, fashioned as a tenon to fit into a draped torso (the join then concealed by drapery), is lost. The proper left ear is chipped. The surface is damaged at the outer end of the proper left eyebrow, to the left of the mouth, and at the left edge of the neck. The nose has been replaced, the glued join concealed. The restoration necessitated some superficial reworking of the lips and chin. In general the head, which is carved in Carrara marble with some mineral inclusions, has the appearance of an ancient piece cleaned and reworked for the antiquities market.

Description: Mosaic slice: the slice has a tomato-red field and has one highly polished surface, perhaps repolished in the 19th century. Traditional scene composed of the nfr-sign in the centre in yellow and black with pale-blue base. White cords bind the heraldic plants of Upper and Lower Egypt to the central stem of the hieroglyph. Below is a conventionalized representation of a lake, the water pale blue, the vertical water lines in dark blue. The lake is outlined in yellow.

Curator's comments: The style is strongly suggestive of an Alexandrian origin.
Description: Circular medallion: in opaque grey-blue glass, matt surface, the reverse flat, the obverse slightly convex. Exceptionally, there was no suspension loop. On the obverse is an idealizing female head in high relief very slightly twisted to the right. The sole attributes surviving are two knobs or bosses on the forehead. Possibly a Tyche is represented. The medallion is very extensively broken and is the wreck of an originally splendid piece.

Polygonal fired clay token; low relief designs on both sides: on obverse - seated figure wearing a high polos hat, reclining on a couch, served by an attendant, with a shield? above containing another bust; on reverse - three seated figures, wearing high polos hats, facing frontally, above them is a female? portrait bust with stars or rosettes either side; worn.

Fragment of wall of closed-form pottery jar in glass-studded ware; on exterior barbotine decoration of vertical lines terminating at both ends in clay cups containing small pieces of coloured glass, turquoise in lower cups, yellow in upper; between vertical lines diagonal leaf-motifs with central ridge of barbotine dots; above main motif remains of horizontal band of small barbotine dots with clay cup.

Curator's comments: This rare type (one of only two specimens known) sets out the Republican-spirited façade of the Principate. The victorious Octavian is posed as toga-clad civilian magistrate proclaiming ‘the laws and rights of the people (of Rome) restored’. Politically acceptable authority in the Senate is suggested by the tally of consulships. Yet despite such Republican titulature he is still obviously a monarch with the coinage produced under the stamp of his image (and a personal authority boosted by being the son of a god – the title Divi F[ilius] having been used since the deification of Julius in 42 BC).
Description: Gold coin.(obverse) Head of Octavian, right.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Content': u'IMP CAESAR DIVI F COS VI', u'Inscription Position': u'obverse', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription'}]

Description: Mosaic slice: a Horus falcon, in profile, standing, facing left on a translucent dark-blue field. The bird is beautifully rendered with polychrome plumage in red, green, white, black, and yellow. The headdress appears to be the double crown but this area is either misfired or damaged. A small hole was bored in the upper background apparently to facilitate  the  attachment. The left edge is broken with the loss of the front of the face and body.

Pottery: coarse ware bowl; pink-orange clay with moderate fine-medium lime and black particles; overall mid-orange slip, dull and patchy, extremely worn on exterior and upper wall on interior; two ear handles with broad ribbon section with single groove; approximately one third of rim and wall, and one handle, missing; traces of heavy white concretion.

Pottery: coarse ware bowl; orange-pink clay with frequent fine inclusions of mica, grits and lime; overall dull orange slip, very worn; broad horizontal rim with short vertical extremity; broad shallow body, lightly carinated with rounded shoulder and splayed flat base; approximately one half of rim and one fifth of wall missing.

Pottery: coarse ware one-handled bottle (lagena/lekythos); red-orange micaceous clay with a red-brown semi-matt slip; white painted decoration of diagonal rays on shoulder, between two pairs of deep grooves; two white wavy bands like the ends of a fillet falling from base of handle; rim broken; two-thirds restored.

Curator's comments: Roman Pottery
Description: Pottery askos in the form of a squatting rabbit, with a handle over the back and a mouth between the ears; dark grey fabric, over-fired or a kiln-second (?).

Bronze lamp with a rounded body and a flat-topped splayed nozzle with an angular tip and a semicircular wick-hole. At the body end of the nozzle are `volute-spines'. The central filling-hole is within a dished area decorated with mouldings. At the rear is a ring handle surmounted by a crescent ornament with knobbed terminals. The raised circular base has internal `lathe-turned' mouldings; there is a small hole through the centre.

Mould-made pottery lamp with two rounded nozzles, a wide rounded shoulder, a grooved band handle at the rear, a lug in the form of an ivy-leaf on each side, and a base-ring, flat within and defined by a groove. The filling-hole is surrounded by a raised rim. The shoulders are decorated with ivy tendrils, leaves and berries. One nozzle is damaged. Within the base-ring are five impressed circles arranged in a cross. Covered with a glossy brown to black slip.

Curator's comments: This object is illustrated in the manuscript catalogue of Pitt-Rivers's second collection. (Cambridge University Library, Add.  9455, vol. 1, p. 217)

Curator's comments: 1878.1-19.264.b has been removed.
Description: Bronze lamp with a rounded body and a flat-topped splayed and fluked nozzle with an almost circular wick-hole. At the body end of the nozzle are `volute-spines' with dished tops, meeting underneath. The wide filling-hole is surrounded by a low rim, and has a step (damaged) for a lid (now lost). At the rear is a suspension-lug on a knob; on top of the nozzle is a duck-head suspension-lug; both are attached to chains (probably modern) coming together at a ring. The base is completely broken away.

Bronze lamp with a rounded body and a voluted nozzle with a rounded tip and an oval wick-hole. The beaded nozzle-volutes form a raised edge to the nozzle-top, which has an air-hole and a sunken branch pattern. The dished filling-hole area has a beaded rim; within is a small filling-hole with a moulded edge. At the rear is a ring handle with raised edges and transverse grooves, surmounted by a crescent ornament with grooved decoration and a ring-and-dot pattern. The base and the underside of the nozzle are broken away; there are holes through the right side of the nozzle.

Curator's comments: The decoration, thickness, colour and condition strongly suggest that this was originally part of the same plaque as fragments 1886.11-17.43 and 1886.11-17.38.
Description: Fragment of a plaque in three-layer translucent dark blue and opaque white cameo glass. The translucent dark blue is partly sandwiched between opaque white. The decoration, in white, may show fruit (a quince?) with leaves, or perhaps a large stemmed flower with circular centre and several flamboyant petals.

Curator's comments: The decoration, thickness, colour and condition strongly suggest that this was originally part of the same plaque as fragments 1886.11-17.48 and 1886.11-17.31.
Description: Fragment of plaque in three-layer translucent dark blue and opaque white cameo glass.  The translucent blue is partly sandwiched between the opaque white. One edge of the plaque survives. The decoration, in white, shows vegetal motifs comprising part of an acanthus leaf on the left and a stem or branch on the right.

Curator's comments: The decoration, thickness, colour and condition strongly suggest that this was originally part of the same plaque as fragments 1886.11-17.43 and 1886.11-17.31.
Description: Fragment of a plaque in three-layered translucent dark blue and opaque white cameo glass. The translucent blue is partly sandwiched between opaque white. The decoration, in white, shows, at the left, part of an acanthus leaf and, at the right, a stem with a bract separating the upper and lower parts. There are traces of another element to the right of the stem.

Description: Pottery: Colour-Coated Ware bowl; mid-brown clay with grey-brown finish; dark brown slip over upper body and all over interior, dull, patchily applied and mottled; thickened rounded rim, broad deep carinated body with straight upper wall and broad ring foot; remains of white encrustation over much of exterior; four bands of rouletting at and below carination on lower wall; very large crack from rim, round lower wall and almost to rim on other side; large piece of upper wall missing.

Curator's comments: This miniature cameo bust represents a veiled young man in three-quarter left profile (the nose is missing), undoubtedly Octavian, the young Augustus, whose distinguishable hairstyle follows that of the so-called ‘Actium type’. However, the strong similarities to the facial features of a similarly veiled statue head of the so-called ‘Prima Porta type’, kept at the Archaeological Museum at Chiusi, Italy (Inv. 3182), should be noted. He is wearing a tunic, and a toga which is pulled up to cover the back of the head, while a laurel wreath is visible on the front. The details in the drapery of both garments, as well as the powerful gaze and overall impression of emotion, show the delicacy and skill of the carving of this bust. Traces of metal, possibly gold, are still visible throughout the front of the portrait, particularly in the hair and drapery (Thoresen), and confirm the prestigious character of the object.
Description: Chalcedony cameo portrait bust, probably Octavian, laureate and veiled with his toga.

Curator's comments: Gold necklace, composed of (a) two sets of six gold cylinders of thin ribbed gold, each with a berry attached to their middle point ; (b) a set of double ribbed cylinders each with a rosette of seven petals at one end ; {c) in the centre is a pendent figure of Eros (unworked at back), with a sash passing across his back and twisted round his arms. With his 1. hand he holds out a plaque, embossed with a comic mask.
Description: A pendant figure of Eros (unworked at back), with a sash passing across his back and twisted round his arms. With his left hand he holds out a plaque, embossed with a comic mask.

Associated names: Named in inscription: C Asinius Gallus
Curator's comments: Caius Asinius Gallus was was a friend of the emperor Augustus, and governor of the province of Asia in 6/5 BC, when this inscription was set up. He became the son-in-law of Marcus Agrippa  after marrying Vipsania Agrippa, former wife of the emperor Tiberius (before he was emperor). The cognomen of Caius Asinius Gallus was erased from this inscription after he suffered the damnatio memoriae by the emperor Tiberius in AD 30, whom he had opposed.
Description: Block of white marble with a bi-lingual inscription in Latin and Greek.  The inscription records the rebuilding of the Artemision at Ephesus by the order of the emperor Augustus in 6BC.
Inscriptions: [{u'Inscription Translation': u'The Emperor Caesar Augustus, son of a god, consul for the twelfth time, with tribunician power for the eighteenth time, chief priest, arranged for the temple of Diana and the Augusteum to be fortified (i.e. surrounded) by a wall, (to be funded) from (their) income, under the proconsul C. Asinius Gallus, (and) by the overseer of the works, Sextus Lartidius, legate.', u'Inscription Content': u'IMP · CAESAR · DIVI · F · AVG · COS · XII · TR · POT · XVIII · PONTIFEX MAXIMVS · EX · REDITV · DIANAE · FANVM · ET · AVGVSTEVM · MVRO MVNIENDVM · CVRAVIT · C · ASINIO · [[GALLO PRO COS]] · CVRATORE SEX · LARTIDIO · LEG (see IGBM. DXXII for Greek inscription)', u'Inscription Transliteration': u'Imp(erator) Caesar divi f(ilius) Aug(ustus) co(n)s(ul) XII tr(ibunicia) pot(estate) XVIII pontifex maximus ex reditu Dianae fanum et Augusteum muro muniendum curavit C(aio) Asinio [[Gallo proco(n)s(uli)]] curatore Sex(to) Lartidio leg(ato) (see IGBM. DXXII for Greek inscription)', u'Inscription Language': u'Latin/Greek', u'Inscription Type': u'inscription', u'Inscription Comment': u'(J.T.Wood; Discoveries at Ephesus, 1877. Curator's comments: Octavian's IMP CAESAR coinage was a celebration of the final triumph of the Caesarian cause in the civil wars. It addressed the many themes of the 'new order' and was most appropriate to the period preceding the young Caesar's magnificent triple triumph in mid-August 29 BC. Its large volume was made possible by the wealth of the Ptolemaic treasury, now safely in Roman hands, and was necessary for the recompense of soldiers newly retired from the disbanded legions and the financing of the lavish festivities in the capital. It seems probable that this was the first type to be issued in the IMP CAESAR series as it supersedes an otherwise identical denarius with the earlier CAESAR DIVI F legend (RIC 263). It seems likely that the reverse type commemorates Octavian's victorious entry into Alexandria on August 1, while the obverse looks back to Actium.
Description: Silver coin; ancient forgery, pierced for suspension.(obverse) Victory, draped, standing right on prow, holding out wreath in right hand and holding palm in left hand over left shoulder.

Curator's comments: Stead 2006
Description: Iron sword and copper alloy sheath. The blade of a sword visible only through splits at the edges of the copper-alloy scabbard. It has been about 830 mm long and some 40 mm wide. It lacks a tang, but there is a copper-alloy hilt end with a rib on top. The hilt end is decorated front and back with circles within bands that taper to exaggerate its arc and then expand towards the edges. The circles on the back have been engraved or stamped in the original wax and have hatched backgrounds, but the four central circles on the front are hollowed, possibly for applied ornament.

Curator's comments: Surface condition poor,  suggesting a Lower Egyptian origin,  but in its original condition this was clearly a spectacular piece.
Description: Gaming-piece: in the shape of a truncated cone in opaque red glass, much of it now turned green. Around the greater part of the body are continuous registers of alternating wide and narrow rectangles. Each wide rectangle is outlined in opaque green glass (possibly originally red) and encloses a mosaic slice of very fine quality and small scale.  The subject is a Horus falcon in red, yellow, white, black, and green standing on a yellow and black base against a white background. The narrow rectangles also had mosaic glass inlays but these are so decayed that their subject cannot be identified. Vertically pierced.

Description: Handle ornament broken from a terracotta lamp: this fragmentary triangular handle-ornament from a lamp shows a warship with a triple ram at the prow, a centaur figurehead, and a bank of oars. A decorative gunwale is adorned with a crested helmet and a circular shield. On deck are soldiers, helmeted, with swords and oval 'Celtic' shields. Behind them rise either groups of spears or shrouds of the ship's rigging, between which is a military standard. The centaur is shown as about to throw a rock and this may refer to the menacing centaurs on the prows of Antony's ships at Actium. The left side and the top are missing. Buff clay, some mica, covered with a brown slip.

Description: Sard intaglio: the subject is portrayed with  extraordinary refinement of detail and manipulation of the planes of view. The tightly curled hair recedes at the temple. The brow is deeply lined, bulging above the long, slightly hooked nose. Beside the hooded eye are crow's feet; the cheeks are deeply lined, the mouth slightly open, and the chin prominent. The neck, creased at the back, is turned at the shoulder. The Adam's apple projects to reflect the turn at the front. The subject is evidently a Roman of mature years, of the mid-first century BC; the hairstyle may be compared to Egyptian and Roman portraits from Egypt. The subject has been identified as the orator and statesman Marcus Tullius Cicero, who was the political opponent of both Julius Caesar and Mark Antony.

Pendant earring: the earring is in a pale gold and is fairly crudely worked. The upper part of the ornament is a crescentic plaque with a symmetrical series of volutes below, formed of repousse-gold sheet. An S-shaped hook is soldered to the back and the wire runs up to support a bead within the horns of the crescent. Hanging from three loops, which are attached behind the volutes, are wires covered by narrow cones of sheet gold, and terminating in beads. The bead within the crescent is made of hollow glass. The other beads appear to be pearls.

Curator's comments: Some elements of the necklace may well be alien, though no doubt ancient, in particular the green bead and the uraeus. In the absence of any history, there must be some doubt about the overall integrity of the piece, though its appearance is akin to the hair ornament worn by the subjects of some Neronian portraits.
Description: Bead ornament with pendant discs: the beads are threaded on modern brass wire. The two principal types of bead are small orange-red hardstones described by Marshall as garnet, but looking more like cornelian, and spacer beads formed of a short spiral of fine gold wire. In addition, there are two small, blue-green faience beads and seven dark blue beads, probably of glass. Hanging from the string of beads are twenty-nine gold-and-pearl pendants. These consist of a pearl capped with gold at each end and a wire loop from which hangs a small gold disc with a cut-out (making a crescent shape) occupied by another small pearl on a wire. The disc element of one pendant is lost, and next to this defective pendant are two additional ornaments, an oval dark green glass bead and a small faience, uraeus pendant. The twisted gold wire which attaches the uraeus to the necklace looks modern.

Additional description etc by JCK 24/10/1995.
Description:
Length of buff-coloured wool cloth, backed with printed cotton cloth, to which
is attached in a long zig-zag or snaking line, a series of small calcined
univalve shells, forming a solid rectangle along the length of this belt-shaped piece of material. At one end are attached six long shell beads, from the columns of large univalves, and five small flat shell beads, all archaeological and much calcined. This may or may not reflect an original assemblage from a grave, or it may be a group of disparate finds, possible from a context including shell middens.

Curator's comments: Published: H. Tait (ed.), Masterpieces of Glass, London, 1968, no 88; Exh. cat., Glass of the Caesars, Milan, 1987, no 154.
Description: Two portions of a bowl; transparent glass; each composed of three fragments. Ornamented with twenty-one gilded medallions, protected at the back with green and blue glass; in the larger ones are figure subjects, and in the smaller ones are stars or eight-petalled flowers all arranged in concentric circles. Of the four outermost remaining medallions, one represents Jesus or Moses with the rod of power, a second Adam and Eve, a third the sacrifice of Isaac and the fourth Susannah(?). The eight remaining figured medallions illustrate three subjects: the stories of Jonah, Daniel and the Three Children of Babylon.

Curator's comments:
Such double-walled cups decorated with scenes in relief were a Hellenistic innovation, replaced in the later first century AD by solid cast vessels. It is likely that the cup was commissioned by wealthy members of a Greek community, perhaps one of the major cities of the Eastern Mediterranean. The cup is said to have been found in Palestine with coins of the Emperor Claudius (41 - 54 AD).
The age and status of the figures in both scenes is carefully shown. The bearded man and youths are shown in a style typical of the classicizing art of the reign of the emperor Augustus (30BC - AD14), and can probably be dated more closely to approximately 15BC-AD15. The musical instruments, wreaths and mantles suggest a cultured, Hellenized setting. Both partners in the reverse scene have long locks of hair, the youth's bound up, the boy's loose. Such locks were worn by Greek boys, and were offered to the gods in a rite celebrated at puberty.
Description:
A silver stemmed drinking-cup originally with two vertical handles (now lost) comprising decorated outer casing (now split in one place) enclosing, in order to facilitate both drinking and cleaning, the drinking vessel. The handles and foot were cast separately. The decorative scenes on the outer casing were raised by hammering and elaborated with chased and engraved details, some enhanced by gilding (now lost). 
The decoration consists of two scenes of male homosexual love-making, set in interiors elaborated with textile hangings. On the obverse the older, active lover (erastes) is bearded and wears a wreath, while the younger, passive partner (eromenos) is a beardless youth. On the reverse the erastes is a beardless youth, crowned with a wreath, and the eromenos is a boy.  The boy at the door with short hair, who is observing the scene, is a probably a slave.

See also cameo disc 1945.0927.2.Jenkins & Sloan 1996
Description: Amphora in translucent dark cobalt blue and opaque white cameo glass. The cylindrical neck widens out to a sloping shoulder and ovoid body, whose squatness is emphasized by the lack of a foot. Everted mouth with rounded rim which is cut very unevenly on the upper side so that it is not horizontal; below this the neck curves out smoothly to the carination of the shoulder. Handles from the centre of the neck to the shoulder. The disc base (1945.9-27.2) is discussed separately.  A separate Registration Number (1948.10-18.1) was assigned to approximately forty small fragments, most of which were incorporated during the most recent restoration.
